<TITLE> Bombs kill 32 at centre for displaced in Pakistan </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 KACHA PAKHA, Pakistan, April 17 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Two suicide bombings at a centre for people displaced by a Pakistani military offensive against militants killed at least 32 people and wounded 80 on Saturday, an official said. The first attacker, disguised as a woman in an all-enveloping burqa dress, was followed seconds later by a teenager who blew himself up, said local commissioner Khalid Khan Omarzai. "It was huge and caused most of the deaths," he said. They struck as about 300 people displaced by fighting were registering at an office in the village of Kacha Pakha in the northwest of the country, hoping to get food items, officials said. Pakistan's military has carried out a series of crackdowns against homegrown al Qaeda-backed Taliban fighters seeking to topple the government. But the measures have failed to weaken the resolve of the Taliban, whose violent suicide bombings have raised questions over the stability of US ally Pakistan. "The blasts were so powerful that the limbs of people scattered throughout the area. People are searching limbs of their dear ones in nearby crop fields," said resident Mohammad Qasim. Shoes and blood-stained clothes lay scattered. A group affiliated with Pakistan's Taliban claimed responsibility for the attacks on Saturday. The military says its latest operations, in the Orakzai and Khyber and Kurram regions, have killed hundreds of militants, casualty tolls that were not possible to confirm independent
